# Why This Works

Sorting blocked rows and blocked columns lets us identify every continuous free segment. Since any valid rectangle must lie entirely within one free row segment and one free column segment, the largest rectangle is simply the product of the longest such segments. Because blocked rows and columns are independent, multiplying these two maximum lengths always yields the largest continuous unblocked submatrix.

