# Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

> Since every blocked cell disables its entire row and column, the actual blocked cell positions are not important after extracting the row and column indices. I separate blocked rows and blocked columns, sort them independently, and compute the largest consecutive gap between blocked rows and between blocked columns. These gaps represent the longest continuous free row and column segments. The maximum unblocked rectangle is the product of these two lengths. Sorting dominates the complexity, giving **O(k log k)** time and **O(k)** space.

---

# Key Takeaways

* Entire rows and columns are blocked.
* Only blocked row numbers and blocked column numbers matter.
* Sorting converts the problem into finding maximum gaps.
* Largest rectangle = longest free rows × longest free columns.
* Meets the expected complexity of **O(k log k)**.

---

# Common Mistakes

❌ Forgetting the segment **before the first blocked row** (`rows[0] - 1`).

❌ Forgetting the segment **after the last blocked row** (`n - rows[-1]`).

❌ Missing the `-1` when computing the gap between blocked rows or columns.

❌ Not handling the case `k == 0`.

❌ Assuming the blocked cell itself is the only blocked position instead of its entire row and column.

